            <h3>I ditched my DSLR & iPhone, for a 50 year old camera.</h3><br>
            <p>It's been a few years since a camera repair man in Orem Utah by the name of Kew introduced me to Medium format, and sold me a $100 dollar Rolleicord. Ever since I've been completely enamored by the 120mm format. Part of it is the nostalgia for a simpler time, were photos weren't so easy to get, and development was an art and a science. Part of it is the mir fact that photos from a camera with a larger sensor area (to borrow modern camera speech) produce different types of images, which is something we have forgotten in the era of camera phones and mirrorless cameras. I've brought my nearly 70 year old camera on hikes through the tetons, and canyons in Moab, I've rock climbed with it and weathered storms with it. Something about this camera and format brings new life and meaning to the art of landscape photography, similar to the way a digital recording will never sound quite as good as a record. Time and time again I find my self leaving my DSLR home and bringing a medium format camera instead. </p>
            <p>Over the last few years I've collected a couple dozen shots from all over the US, bellow are a collection of shots that both show my transformation as an artist and my growing understanding of this vibrant medium. </p>
            
